Here's how to implement this in .NET MAUI Shell:

**1. Override `OnBackButtonPressed` and add a custom toolbar item:**

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    public EditProductPage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        Shell.SetBackButtonBehavior(this, new BackButtonBehavior
        {
            TextOverride = "Cancel",
            Command = new Command(async () => await TryNavigateBack())
        });
    }

    // Handles hardware/software back button (Android, etc.)
    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            MainThread.BeginInvokeOnMainThread(async () => await TryNavigateBack());
            return true; // cancel default navigation
        }
        return base.OnBackButtonPressed();
    }

    private async Task TryNavigateBack()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!leave) return; // user chose to stay
        }

        await Shell.Current.GoBackAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- `Shell.SetBackButtonBehavior` with `TextOverride = "Cancel"` replaces the back arrow with a "Cancel" label and hooks your custom command.
- `OnBackButtonPressed` returning `true` cancels the default back navigation (covers Android hardware back and swipe gestures).
- `DisplayAlert` shows the confirmation; only call `GoBackAsync()` if the user confirms.

> **Note:** iOS swipe-back gesture bypasses `OnBackButtonPressed`. To block it, disable it on this page:
> ```csharp
> Shell.SetPresentationMode(this, PresentationMode.ModalAnimated);
> // or in your platform-specific code, disable the gesture recognizer
> ```
> Alternatively, push the page modally (`Shell.Current.GoToAsync("page", animate: true)` with `ShellNavigationQueryAttribute`) so the swipe-back doesn't apply.
